# Video Pipeline: Experiment-Driven Development

## Parse configs live in the DB, not in code

All configurations are rows in `parseConfigs`. Do not edit `pass-definitions.ts`
constants or introduce new hardcoded pass objects.

❌ Adding a constant to `pass-definitions.ts` or changing `DEFAULT_PRIMARY_PASS`
✅ Creating a `parseConfig` row in `/admin/parse-configs` and referencing it from
   an experiment arm

`DEFAULT_PRIMARY_PASS` and `SHADOW_PASS_AB` are legacy fallbacks only — used when
no `configAssignment` or `experimentArmId` is set on a group.

## Shadow pass changes require a campaign

`enqueue-shadow-pass.ts` reads `group.experimentArmId` → `experimentArms.configId`
to decide which config to run. Never add a hardcoded shadow config — create an
`experimentCampaign` with a treatment arm pointing at the new `parseConfig`.

## Every experiment is scoped to one event format

`experimentCampaigns.scoreTarget` is NOT NULL. Never create or activate a campaign
with `scoreTarget = null`. Event formats have fundamentally different video
structures (frame counts, OCR layout, scroll behavior, score positions) so
results from Alliance Exercise are not comparable to Desert Storm or Zombie Siege.

Run one campaign per event format. If you need to test a config across formats,
run parallel campaigns — one per `scoreTarget`.

## Analytics must always segment by scoreTarget

When querying or displaying analytics, `score_target` is always a GROUP BY
dimension. Never display a flat thumbs-up % or quality score that mixes event
types without a clear "⚠ mixed event types" warning.

## Promoting to primary requires a concluded experiment

A config becomes primary for a target only via a `configAssignments` row. Required
before writing that row:
- Arm has ≥ 50 rated jobs
- Thumbs-up % or quality bucket is measurably better than the control arm
- Campaign `status` is `concluded` with a written `conclusion`

## Population check before concluding

Before setting `status = 'concluded'`, confirm the population panel shows the
expected `scoreTarget` distribution. A result driven by a single unusual event
instance is not generalizable — verify the sample spans multiple event occurrences.

## New score targets start without a config assignment

When a new `scoreTarget` or `boardKey` is introduced, do not hardcode a
target-specific config. Let the first uploads use the default and set up an
experiment to find the best config for that target.

## Check analytics before tuning traffic weights

Before changing `trafficPercent` or arm `trafficWeight`, verify current arm
performance at `/admin/video-jobs/analytics?scoreTarget=<type>`.
Document the reason for the change in the campaign `description`.
